set_stats but the password should not be visible 

I’m checking the Ansible and Controller docs on set_stats and secret masking, because this is one of those cases where the safe answer is usually “don’t pass raw secrets through workflow artifacts.” Then I’ll show the safest pattern for your role.

Thought for 36s

Use set_stats only for non-secret metadata, not for the actual password.

Reason: in AWX/Controller workflows, values created with set_stats are stored in the parent job’s artifacts and inherited by downstream jobs. no_log: true protects task output and logs, but it does not turn workflow artifacts into a secure secret store. Also, if show_custom_stats is enabled, custom stats can be shown in the play recap.

So for your case, the safe pattern is:

retrieve the password with no_log: true
create was_password as a normal fact with set_fact
publish only non-sensitive info with set_stats, such as which user vars were processed, which password var names were created, and success/failure status
in downstream workflow jobs, call the CyberArk role again instead of trying to pass the raw password through artifacts
What not to do

Do not do this:

- name: Unsafe - publishes raw password into workflow artifacts
  ansible.builtin.set_stats:
    data:
      was_password: "{{ __cyberark_password_value }}"
  no_log: true

That hides console/log output, but the secret still becomes artifact data for downstream nodes. That is the part to avoid. This is an inference from how set_stats artifacts are inherited in workflows plus how no_log is documented to affect logging/output.

Safe pattern for your role

Update the end of the role like this:

---
- name: Publish individual *_password facts for current job only
  ansible.builtin.set_fact:
    "{{ item.item.password_var_name }}": "{{ item.result.Content | default(item.Content) }}"
  loop: "{{ __cyberark_fetch.results }}"
  loop_control:
    label: "{{ item.item.password_var_name }}"
  no_log: true

- name: Build non-secret workflow artifact payload
  ansible.builtin.set_fact:
    __cyberark_artifact_payload: >-
      {{
        (__cyberark_artifact_payload | default({})) |
        combine({
          item.item.user_var_name: {
            'password_var_name': item.item.password_var_name,
            'retrieved': true
          }
        })
      }}
  loop: "{{ __cyberark_fetch.results }}"
  loop_control:
    label: "{{ item.item.user_var_name }}"
  no_log: true

- name: Publish only non-secret metadata to downstream workflow nodes
  ansible.builtin.set_stats:
    data:
      cyberark_retrieved_users: "{{ __cyberark_artifact_payload }}"
    aggregate: true
    per_host: false
  no_log: true

That gives you artifacts like:

cyberark_retrieved_users:
  was_user:
    password_var_name: was_password
    retrieved: true
  db_user:
    password_var_name: db_password
    retrieved: true

No raw password is stored in workflow artifacts.

How to use it

If you run with:

was_user: wasadmin
db_user: dbadmin

the current job will still get these in memory:

was_password: <real password>
db_password: <real password>

but the workflow artifacts will contain only:

cyberark_retrieved_users:
  was_user:
    password_var_name: was_password
    retrieved: true
  db_user:
    password_var_name: db_password
    retrieved: true

So downstream jobs know what to retrieve, but not the password itself.

Best practice for downstream workflow nodes

In the next job template, do this again:

- name: Retrieve required passwords again in downstream node
  ansible.builtin.import_role:
    name: cyberark_ccp_password
  vars:
    cyberark_ccp_url: "https://ccp.company.com"
    cyberark_app_id: "AnsibleCertAuthApp"
    cyberark_safe: "MiddlewareSafe"
    cyberark_user_var_names: "{{ cyberark_retrieved_users.keys() | list }}"

That way:

workflow artifacts carry only references
each node retrieves the secret directly from CyberArk when needed
the password never travels through set_stats artifacts
Important note

Even with show_custom_stats = false, that only controls whether custom stats appear in the recap. It does not change the fact that workflow jobs inherit set_stats artifact data.

So the rule is:

set_fact + no_log: true for the real password
set_stats only for non-secret references/status
downstream jobs should fetch secrets again from CyberArk

